Review_Title: Wireless connection issues and/or college student? PLEASE READ!!!
Review_Content: PROBLEM SOLVED! For anyone trying to set up this HP Envy 6055e wireless printer at college or where a router is not accessible, I’m writing this review in hopes of saving you time and frustration (at least this is what worked for us). My daughter and I were trying to set up her new printer at college using the enclosed instructions. As directed, she unpacked the printer and plugged it in. She’ll be accessing the printer from her iPhone and MacBook, so she downloaded the HP Smart App on both devices. Using the Smart App on her phone, we received a message that setup should be completed on her laptop first. During this process and after repeated error messages saying the wi-fi password was incorrect (even though it was NOT), we decided to try another method. I learned from her university’s tech page that personal printers are allowed, but must be connected through a direct connection between her printer and her device(s). In other words, her printer cannot connect to the university wi-fi, but should communicate with her devices via “HP Wi-Fi Direct”. Realizing that we needed the printer’s Wi-Fi Direct Name and Password we had to figure out how to retrieve it, since printer setup had not been completed. We decided to re-start the setup process (if I remember correctly) – we powered off the printer and unplugged it for a minute, then plugged it back in and turned it on. We loaded a small amount of paper and inserted the ink cartridges. I’m unable to post the external link, but we searched HP support for HP Envy 6055e Wi-Fi Direct setup. Using the step-by-step instructions, we were able to use the “Information” button on the printer to print out the necessary Wi-Fi Direct Name and Password, TURN ON Wi-Fi Direct and proceed with setup.After several frustrating hours my daughter was finally able to complete setup on both devices and print successfully. The most important thing to note – whether printing from a phone or laptop –  “if you want to print web content, such as an email or cloud-based document, open the item before proceeding.” To sum up, use your regular wi-fi connection to open your document, then use your device’s wi-fi network menu to select your printer (starting with DIRECT and your printer model) and proceed to print.The process sounds complicated, but is fairly straightforward when following the HP Wi-Fi Direct Setup.Although we had hoped the printer would be more user-friendly, we were ultimately satisfied to find a way for her to use it on campus.FYI - During setup we chose NOT to enroll in HP+ or HP Instant InkGood Luck!

Review_Title: Unless you want to use it with your smartphone..................................

My wife is a school teacher and needed a RELIABLE printer.THIS UNIT IS NOT IT!!!! IT IS A PIECE OF JUNK. The controls on the front do not give the user any idea if something is wrong unless you have the machine in front of you and see the flashing "X" button. We found out too late that it works fine if you want to use your smartphone to operate it, OTHERWISE, forget it. The "HP Connect" for the computer is also useless with this unit. Another thing, if you want to send a print job to the unit once it has gone into sleep mode, you have to figure out how to "wake it up" so you can print, which means that you have to go over the machine and manually start pushing buttons and hope that works. We found it easier to just unplug and then re-plug it to get it to wake up. One last thing, if you want to print a lot, then you are going to be putting lots of paper into it as the carriage does not hold very much paper.In other words, unless you want to do all of your scanning, copying, and printing solely with your phone, or use it once in a while, forget this unit. It is WORTHLESS!!!!!If there were a ZERO STAR place, I would give it a zero. A total waste of money, and a waste of $150. dollars, plus INK.As a result, we purchased another HP machine and it works great.

Calling this week to see if they can just send me a DIFFERENT model.  I'm going thru the warrantee.  Nightmare!  I used to recommend HP but the poor customer service ruined that.

My Envy 6455e will be one year old in March 2024.  I have spent over 6 hours on the phone with Tech Support, Insta Ink, and they even tried blaming my internet provider to pass the buck. I still have a non-working printer. I have not been able to print in almost a month. I've escalated the call today with a supervisor and they are sending me another set of Ink Cartridges because the last brand-new ones didn't fix the issue. The one-year warranty is a joke, and they continue to send non-working replacements. This will be my 3rd when the ink doesn't fix the issue. The last replacement came dirty with coffee drips on it. I've recommended HP for years but they don't seem to care about their customers. I am now shopping for an Epson printer.

Review_Title: Lots of problems that are hard to fix
Review_Content: Had major problems getting the all in one printer to work.  I spent hours on the phone with HP advanced techs.  Finally they said I had bought a lemon.  I considered exchanging it for a different brand but when I consulted Apple's web site they recommended an HP printer.  Finally on the last night before I could return it the printer started printing.  It was an excellent buy regular $150 on sale for $89 so I kept it.  The next week it stopped printing.  Now in order to print I unplug the printer and restart my computer and then it works.  But if I had to do it over again I would buy a different brand or a better HP model.  One incentive for keeping it is the HP Ink replacement program.  It is inexpensive and efficient.

I bought this HP Envy printer to print pictures and I am ready to toss it out. I have followed all directions and even call the Geek Squad and did what they said with NO luck. What am I suppose to do. Can I return it and buy something that works.
